defaultNovo Nordisk strongly welcomes the focus on diabetes being taken by the Health Committee.
default 
defaultDiabetes is rapidly becoming one of the most pressing public health issues 
defaultwith three 
defaultmillion people
default now diagnosed with diabetes and
default 850,000 
defaultpeop
defaultl
defaulte
default 
defaultunaware they have the condition
default,
default 
default.
default 
defaultIn the next 20 years, the number of people 
defaultdiagnosed with 
defaultdiabetes is expected to rise to 
default5.6
default million at a cost of £3
default9.8
default billion to the NHS and to the wider economy
default.
default 
default&#xa0;default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDiabetes significantly increases the risk of developing a number of potentially life-threatening complications including stroke, cardiac failure and renal failure, as well as blindness and major limb amputations.
default 
defaultIt is estimated 80% of the cost of diabetes is avoidable through effective and timely interventions to prevent complications
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA clear and comprehensive strategy for tackling diabetes is urgently needed.
default 
defaultWe await the publication of Action for Diabetes, which we hope will provide that strategy.
default 
defaultWhile we are encouraged by the work that is taking place to ensure diabetes remains a priority for the NHS, 
defaultwe believe that the implementation document must take a holistic view of care in the NHS and beyond.
default 
defaultIn particular, the implementation guide must address how to reduce the variations that exist in diabetes care and outcomes across the country.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are already levers and incentives in place to improve diabetes care, for example the Quality and Outcomes Framework
default (QOF)
default incentivises GPs to undertake a variety of care processes for people with diabetes.
default 
defaultThese must be kept under constant review in order to ensure they are fit for purpose.
default 
defaultFurthermore, new levers should be developed and effectively implemented so that care for people with diabetes 
defaultis constantly improving.
default 
defaultThese should include additional indicators on diabetes in the QOF and the clinical commissioning group outcome indicator set (CCGOIS).
default 
defaultFurthermore, Commissioning for Quality and Innovation (CQUIN) payments should be developed and implemented to drive further improvement across the NHS.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a wealth of evidence linking rising rates of diabetes to rising rates of obesity.
default 
defaultAn obese man is five times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes 
defaultthan an average weight man 
defaultand an obese women is more than thirteen times more likely
default.
default 
defaultIn England, 25% of adults are obese, with 42% of men and 32% of women overweight
default.
default 
defaultIt is predicted that if no action is taken, 60% of men, 50% of women and 25% of children in Britain would be obese by 2050
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSeveral European countries have introduced taxes on unhealthy food and beverages, such as sugary drinks, as part of their efforts to counter obesity
default.
default 
defaultWhile the impact of imposing a tax on sugary drinks is unknown, the Government must ensure manufacturers follow the voluntary measures laid down in the Responsibility Deal.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs of April 2013, obesity has become part of the Public Health Domain of the Quality and Outcomes Framework, which will be managed by Public Health England (PHE).
default 
defaultIt is essential that PHE implements preventative measures to ensure people, particularly children, are supported to moderate their sugar and fat consumption
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhen people do develop diabetes, effective integrated care will be key to ensuring that they receive the care they need and are not exposed to needless risk of complications.
default 
defaultThe types of services which the average person with diabetes will need access to will depend on the specific nature of their condition, their own profile and their place in the care pathway.
default 
defaultThese can include: screening and diagnostic tests; assessments of risk factors and complications; dietary advice; lifestyle and exercise advice; education; glycaemic control and monitoring; Chronic Heart Disease risk factor control and targets; specialist referrals and specialist nursing; diabetes foot assessments and podiatry services; treatment of hypertension
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has recommended that all people 
defaultwith diabetes receive nine
default health
defaultcare
default checks
default.
default 
defaultEnsuring that people with diabetes receive the nine care processes recommended by NICE will require close working be
defaulttween healthcare professionals
default across the NHS.
default 
defaultThe challenge for the new system is to break down boundaries between different parts of the health and care system.
default 
defaultThere is a
defaultn
default opportunity for
default health and wellbeing boards
default 
default(
defaultHWB
defaults
default)
default to lead this agenda, given the representation of both the NHS and local government on these boards.
default 
defaultS
defaultilo-
defaulted
default budgets have been a barrier to integrated care and 
defaultHWBs
default should make a concerted effort to pool budgets across different areas of the care pathway to improve services for patients.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis should be coupled with reforms to tariffs for services for patients with long-term conditions which continue to act as an obstacle to delivering a joined-up system.
default 
defaultThe year of care tariff for long-term conditions presents a real opportunity to move away from paying providers by episode of care and instead treating patients as individuals with complex care needs by focusing more on prevention and condition management in the community.
default 
defaultThis will improve outcomes for patients and deliver much needed efficiencies in the way care is delivered.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNovo Nordisk further welcomes the focus of the committee’s investigation of the readiness of social care services to treat patients with long-term conditions, such as diabetes, in the community.
default 
defaultEvery year thousands of people enter the social care system, the majority of whom are over the age of 65.
default 
defaultT
defaulthe prevalence of diabetes amongst the over 65s is higher than in the general population, yet little is known about the prevalence of diabetes amongst social care users.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2007, the Department of Health estimated that 1 in 20 people with diabetes incur social services costs.
default 
defaultThe presence of complications increased social services costs four-fold
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is widespread recognition that a rapidly ageing society means more people living with chronic long-term health conditions, such as diabetes, placing pressure on health and social care costs
default.
default 
defaultA report by the House of Lords Select Committee on Public Service and Demographic Change predicted that the demand for health and social care for people with diabetes in England and Wales will increase by 45% from 2010 to 2030
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSocial care services must work closely with health services
default to
default ensure that social care users receive the treatment and support they need to maintain good blood glucose and to prevent complications which will result in hospital admissions.
default 
defaultThis will become increasin
defaultg acute as the older population, and consequently demand placed on adult social care and health services, 
defaultrises.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe scale of the challenge to social care services of an ageing population has been clearly demonstrated by the Barnet ‘Graph of Doom’
default.
default 
defaultIt is essential that local authorities and local health economies are equipped and prepared to meet this challenge.
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMeaningful
default data on the prevalence and management of long-term conditions, such as diabetes, in social care settings
default are
default needed
default.
default 
defaultAs mentioned above there is little comprehensive evidence available on the treatment of long-term conditions in social care.
default 
defaultNovo Nordisk is undertaking work to 
defaultuncover the significant contribution of diabetes to local authority social care costs
default.
default 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe complications related to diabetes are not just physical.
default 
defaultNovo Nordisk’s Diabetes Attitudes, Wishes and Needs 
default(DAWN2) 
defaultproject asked people with diabetes about their experiences of having the condition.
default 
defaultAcross all people with diabetes, sleeping problems and depression were the most commonly reported
default.
default 
defaultI
defaultt is estimated that people with diabetes are two to three times more likely to have depression than the rest of the population
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is essential that the mental health of people with long-term conditions, such as diabetes, is considered alongside and equal to their physical wellbeing. 
defaultFailure 
defaultto support people
default with diabetes
default is associated with poorer glycaemic control, more diabetic complications and poorer medicines adherence
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default7.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs part of the DAWN2 project, Novo Nordisk aims to provide enhanced support and education for people with diabetes in order to improve understanding amongst people with diabetes of the need for good glucose management and to give them the help they need to manage their condition effectively.
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition to 
defaultthe project on
default social care, N
defaultovo Nordisk is currently engaged in a significant project with King’s Health Partners, comprising Guy’s and St Thomas’ Hospital and King’s College Hospital London, to demonstrate how the NHS and the pharmaceutical industry working in partnership can develop a model for sustainable diabetes care, research and education.
default 
defaultThe ambition of this joint working project is to co-create a world-recognised centre for diabetes care, research and education: developing and delivering the most cost-effective, highest quality care, ensuring optimal outcomes to patients served by King’s Health Partners.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe expected outcomes and benefits to patients and the NHS of the joint working project are as follows:
default&#xa0;
